:::summary
The Eastern Orthodox Church is the second-largest Christian denomination in the world, with approximately 260 million members, and traces its origins to the Apostles and the early Church councils. It separated from the Roman Catholic Church in the Great Schism of 1054 and has preserved a distinctive theology centered on *theosis* (deification) — the idea that humans are called to become partakers of the divine nature. Orthodox Christianity has shaped the cultures of Greece, Russia, Serbia, Bulgaria, Romania, Georgia, and much of the Middle East.
:::

